Dear Governor Perdue,

Our names are Marek Wojciechowski and Jill Winkler. As owners and 
operators of Chatham Hill Winery, an urban winery located in the 
Triangle, we would like to express our deepest concern about the serious 
consequences that the proposed 5% sales tax increase on wine.  This 
increase will be disastrous on us and many small businesses in our State 
that directly or indirectly depend on the ability to grow grapes and 
produce wine in North Carolina, an industry that has grown exponentially 
over the last ten years and is proud to contribute over $1 billion in 
economic impact on the state’s economy ($813.3 million according to the 
2005 study conducted by MKF Research).

Due to the depressed economy and over 10% unemployment in our area, we 
see continuous decline in sales of wines produced by Chatham Hill and 
when speaking to our colleagues understand they experience similar 
difficulties.  We as well as wine shops, restaurants, and other 
businesses serving in-state and out-of state tourists and business 
visitors face serious declines in revenues which puts us under the same 
debilitating financial pressures as other businesses within the state.

The proposed 5% tax increase on wine sales can only add to the hardship 
that we and the above mentioned businesses are already facing. If the 5% 
tax is implemented our sales will further decline and our North Carolina 
grape growers, come the 2009 harvest in August-September will face 
reduced demand for their fruit which will jeopardize their ability to 
sustain many of their vineyard operations. All of the above will result 
in business closings, layoffs and further reduction in tax revenues 
(e.g., payroll, income, excise, sales taxes) that our wine industry and 
associated industries contribute to the state and local governments. 
Chatham Hill Winery and many other small businesses whose livelihood 
depend on wine sales are struggling to continue each day with the drop 
in business we have all experienced over the last year.

Chatham Hill Winery is a small family-owned and operated business, as is 
most of the over 80 wineries and 450 vineyards located around the state. 
  This is our livelihood and our lives; we do not have other sources of 
income.  All we have has gone into our dream of creating a wonderful 
product based upon the state’s strong agricultural foundation. We fear 
that implementation of the 5% tax increase on wine that is proposed will 
jeopardize our ability to sustain our businesses until the economy turns 
around.

On behalf of Chatham Hill Winery, our employees, our grape growers, our 
wine distributors and wine retailers, our North Carolina suppliers of 
bottles, corks and cellar reagents, and all small businesses that depend 
on the continued growth and success of the North Carolina wine industry, 
please, please reconsider and eliminate your proposed 5% tax on wine.

We appreciate your consideration and cooperation.

Sincerely yours,
Marek Wojciechowski & Jill Winkler
Chatham Hill Winery
Cary/Morrisville, NC




