Dear Governor Perdue,



This letter is to ask you to please reconsider and eliminate the proposed 5% sales tax on North Carolina wine.  It is our opinion that this proposed sales tax would be disastrous to the North Carolina wine industry.  The proposed 5% sales tax increase on wine would be an extreme hardship on the wineries and would affect other industries such as restaurants, hotels, Bed & Breakfasts, gas stations, etc.  In talking to the wineries in our area everyone is in agreement that the economic situation has drastically affected sales.  An increase in sales tax would certainly be a factor in whether some wineries could survive in this economic climate.



North Carolina is home to 80+ wineries and over 400 vineyards.  A very large majority of these wineries and vineyards are small, family-owned businesses and is their sole source of income.  The wine industry has grown over the last ten years with over 5700 jobs created.  The annual economic impact of the NC wine and grape industry is $813 Million, according to a recent study.  Because of its growth, we get tourist from various states.  These tourist also visit nearby restaurants, stay at hotels and B&Bs, purchase fuel for their cars, and shop in local stores.  If the wineries start closing this would affect t the amount of tourism dollars these tours bring into NC.



As everyone knows the unemployment rate in NC is now over 10%, the wine industry has seen a recent decline in sales just as other industries have seen a decline.  To impose additional taxes on NC wines would cause an additional decline in sales for restaurants, wine shops and other businesses.  This proposed 5% tax increase on wine sales can only add to the hardship we as small business owners face everyday.  This would cause our sales to further decline and would affect the many grape growers who depend on their harvest to sustain their vineyards.  This tax would result in business closings, layoffs and further reduction in the tax revenues by reducing payroll, income, excise taxes, and sales taxes that our wineries and associated industries contribute to the state and local governments. 



On behalf of Lake James Cellars owners, employees, grape growers, wine retailers, restaurants, suppliers to the NC wine industry and all small businesses that depend on the continued growth and success of the NC wine industry, please reconsider and eliminate the proposed 5% tax on wine.



Thank you for your consideration and cooperation,

Mike and Betty Fowler

Lake James Cellars

Glen Alpine NC





